        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was the climax of a series of solemn rites. It consisted of the devotion to the deity, by destruction, of the captives and spoil. The name is from the root ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥrm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘to set apart’ or ‘shut off’ (cp. Ar. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥaram",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘sacred precincts’ and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥarîm",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and was not confined to war. By the earliest code every idolatrous Israelite was put to the ḥerem, E, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:20",
        "children": []
