      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:6-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of idolaters, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:12-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [13–19] of an idolatrous city; P, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 27:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. In war the full process was the slaughter of the conquered population and their cattle, the burning of combustible spoil, and the oblation of the rest to the sanctuary. So in the story of the fall of Jericho and Achan’s trespass, Joshua 6 f. (especially ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:17-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff.), which however contains many editorial additions. But as we see from several narratives and laws, the actual practice varied from time to time under the competing influences of religious feeling, material considerations and humane impulses. The most illustrative passage is 1 Samuel 15. Samuel charges Saul to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "devote",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " all ‘Amaleḳ and their cattle; Saul spares the king and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the best of the cattle",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Either his excuse, that he reserved them for sacrifice, is an afterthought; or from the first he had been unwilling that the best cattle should be rendered by the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " unusable by the people in sacrificial feasts. Was the king moved by feelings of humanity? Samuel condemns his action as disobedience against Jehovah; so absolutely at that time was the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " conceived by the religious leaders. The deuteronomic directions, all in the Sg. address, distinguish between Israel’s treatment of the seven Canaanite nations and of Israelite idolaters on the one side, and their treatment of other nations at a distance:—(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : the seven nations are to be put to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " because of their idolatry and no league with them is allowed; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. their idols are to be burned with the silver and gold on them, for they are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and if used by Israel would make the people ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "devoted to destruction",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Similarly in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f. every Israelite community falling to idolatry shall be devoted, and their city, cattle, and spoil burned to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jehovah thy God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 20:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff directs that distant enemies if they submit shall be spared, though they must become tributary; while if they resist only the males shall be slain, the women, children, cattle and spoil being treated as booty. And in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 20:16-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is repeated that the nations of Palestine ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shall be devoted",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Religious feeling, the desire that Israel shall not be infected by the idolatry from which they ran most risk of infection, is obviously the paramount motive of these laws. But it is remarkable that the only instances of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ḥerem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " recorded in Deut., those against Sîḥôn and ‘Ôg, fully agree neither with the treatment enjoined by the deuteronomic laws against the seven nations, nor with that enjoined against distant enemies, but combine features of both. The captive men, women, and children were slain, but the cattle and spoil reserved for booty, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f., ",
